ponse to surrounding microorganisms, a new SigB role, that could have agronomic impact. SigB is induced when B. subtilis is confronted with phytopathogenic fungi (e.g., Fusarium verticillioides) and halts fungal growth to the benefit of plant growth. In this review, we update the knowledge on the different regulatory networks controlling the activation of SigB and its new roles described during the recent years.},
